)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_012", "formula": "C2H2O3", "iupac_name": "oxoacetic acid", "common_name": "glyoxylate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H2O3/c3-1-2(4)5/h1H,(H,4,5)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_013", "formula": "C4H6O3", "iupac_name": "2-oxobutanoic acid", "common_name": "alpha-ketobutyrate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H6O3/c1-2-3(5)4(6)7/h2H2,1H3,(H,6,7)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_014", "formula": "C6H10O3", "iupac_name": "3-methyl-2-oxopentanoic acid", "common_name": "alpha-keto-beta-methylvalerate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C6H10O3/c1-3-4(2)5(7)6(8)9/h4H,3H2,1-2H3,(H,8,9)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_015", "formula": "C7H10N2O2", "iupac_name": "5-ethyl-4-methylimidazolidine-2,4-dione", "common_name": "isoleucine hydantoin", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}], "reactions": [{"id": "rxn_001", "name": "Hydrothermal CO2 reduction to formate", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_005"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "greigite (Fe3S4), mackinawite (FeS)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline vent conditions, anoxic, H2-rich"}, "mechanism": "Mineral-surface reduction of CO2 by H2 on Fe-S phases yields formate as an early C1 fixation product.", "reasoning": "Fe-S minerals catalyze CO2 reduction under alkaline hydrothermal conditions and are central to iron-sulfur world carbon fixation chemistry; this supplies prebiotic C1 feedstock for downstream aldehyde and keto-acid networks (Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997; Martin & Russell, 2007; Grosch et al., 2022)."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "Hydrothermal Fischer-Tropsch-type formation of acetaldehyde", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_006"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)", "elemental iron (Fe0)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "400-500K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "magnetite (Fe3O4), elemental iron (Fe0)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "anoxic FTT-like hydrothermal setting"}, "mechanism": "CO2/CO hydrogenation on metal-rich mineral surfaces produces reduced C2 carbonyl products including acetaldehyde.", "reasoning": "The literature report notes Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis on metal surfaces as a plausible route to aldehydes relevant to Strecker chemistry and specifically mentions FTT as one possible source of 2-methylbutanal precursors (Pizzarello & Cronin, 2008; Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997)."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Hydrothermal pyruvate formation from CO2 and H2", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_011"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)", "greigite (Fe3S4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "magnetite (Fe3O4), greigite (Fe3S4)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline vent redox gradients"}, "mechanism": "Mineral-mediated multicarbon fixation yields alpha-keto acid products such as pyruvate under reducing vent conditions.", "reasoning": "Pyruvate is an established central prebiotic metabolite in hydrothermal/protometabolic models and is explicitly highlighted in the supplied framework as a hydrothermal product feeding later chemistry; it also underpins the alpha-keto-acid route to isoleucine precursors (Springsteen et al., 2018; Barge et al., 2019)."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Hydrothermal generation of glyoxylate from central carbon chemistry", "inputs": ["mol_005"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["pyrite (FeS2)", "greigite (Fe3S4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-400K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "pyrite (FeS2), greigite (Fe3S4)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "anoxic vent-associated carbonyl chemistry"}, "mechanism": "Fe-S mediated oxidation-state redistribution within reduced C1/C2 carbon pools furnishes glyoxylate as a protometabolic alpha-oxoacid intermediate.", "reasoning": "Glyoxylate is identified in the research summary as a central prebiotic metabolite relevant to alpha-ketobutyrate formation via nonenzymatic network logic, though a specific direct hydrothermal preparation remains underconstrained; this step is included as a connective but plausible protometabolic link grounded in glyoxylate-centered prebiotic metabolism (Springsteen et al., 2018; speculative connector explicitly required to connect literature-supported keto-acid routes)."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Volcanic spark-discharge generation of HCN and NH3", "inputs": ["mol_001"], "outputs": ["mol_003", "mol_004"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "sulfide minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2 (anatase/rutile), sulfide minerals", "aqueous": "false", "other": "volcanic atmosphere with CH4/NH3/CO2/H2S/H2O, electrical discharge, strong UV"}, "mechanism": "Energetic atmospheric processing forms HCN and related reduced nitrogen compounds that dissolve into surface waters.", "reasoning": "HCN and NH3 are core Strecker reagents generated in Miller-type discharge systems; Parker et al. showed H2S-containing volcanic discharge settings are uniquely productive for branched amino acids including isoleucine. Mineral listing is included to satisfy the required surface-agent schema, though the primary energy source here is discharge chemistry rather than heterogeneous catalysis (Miller, 1957; Ring et al., 1972; Parker et al., 2011)."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Surface formation of propanal from acetaldehyde under discharge/radical chemistry", "inputs": ["mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_007"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "sulfide minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2 (anatase/rutile), sulfide minerals", "aqueous": "false", "other": "volcanic spark/radical regime, H2S-enhanced branched-chain precursor formation"}, "mechanism": "Radical homologation and carbonyl-chain growth convert lower aldehydes into C3 aldehydes usable in crossed aldol chemistry.", "reasoning": "The literature identifies radical chemistry during electrical discharge as the key source of branched aldehyde precursors and specifically cites crossed aldol chemistry from smaller aldehydes as a plausible route toward 2-methylbutanal. This step formalizes the smaller-aldehyde buildup needed for that route (Ring et al., 1972; Parker et al., 2011; Pizzarello & Cronin, 2008)."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Surface crossed-aldol route to 2-methylbutanal", "inputs": ["mol_006", "mol_007"], "outputs": ["mol_008"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite (clay)", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "montmorillonite (clay), TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "wet-dry cycling, surface concentration, aldehyde condensation and reduction sequence"}, "mechanism": "Crossed aldol condensation between lower aldehydes followed by dehydration/reduction furnishes the branched C5 aldehyde 2-methylbutanal.", "reasoning": "The supplied research explicitly identifies crossed aldol condensation of acetaldehyde with propanal as one plausible prebiotic route to 2-methylbutanal, the critical Strecker precursor for isoleucine. This is a necessary branching-carbon construction step, though the full nonenzymatic sequence remains incompletely demonstrated experimentally (Pizzarello & Cronin, 2008; speculative-but-literature-grounded connection)."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Surface direct radical formation of 2-methylbutanal in H2S-rich discharge chemistry", "inputs": ["mol_006", "mol_007"], "outputs": ["mol_008"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "sulfide minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2 (anatase/rutile), sulfide minerals", "aqueous": "false", "other": "volcanic spark discharge with H2S, radical recombination of alkyl fragments"}, "mechanism": "Electrical discharge generates alkyl radicals whose recombination and oxidation yield branched aldehydes including 2-methylbutanal.", "reasoning": "The strongest evidence for isoleucine synthesis comes from H2S-containing Miller discharge experiments, where sulfur radical chemistry promoted branched-chain amino acid production. The research specifically identifies radical recombination during discharges as a plausible source of 2-methylbutanal (Ring et al., 1972; Parker et al., 2011; Pizzarello & Cronin, 2008)."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "Surface Strecker addition to isoleucine aminonitrile", "inputs": ["mol_008", "mol_003", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "sulfide minerals, montmorillonite (concentration support)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "aqueous Strecker conditions after atmospheric discharge products dissolve into pools"}, "mechanism": "2-Methylbutanal condenses with NH3 to an imine, followed by HCN addition to form the alpha-aminonitrile.", "reasoning": "This is the dominant and best-supported prebiotic route to isoleucine. The literature explicitly states that isoleucine formation proceeds through Strecker chemistry from 2-methylbutanal, HCN, and ammonia in Miller-type systems, with aminonitrile as the key intermediate (Miller, 1957; Ring et al., 1972; Eckhardt et al., 2022; Parker et al., 2011)."}, {"id": "rxn_010", "name": "Biochemical/prebiotic hydrolysis of isoleucine aminonitrile to isoleucine", "inputs": ["mol_009"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [null, null], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "true", "other": "prolonged hydrolysis in prebiotic pools; racemic isoleucine/alloisoleucine expected"}, "mechanism": "Aminonitrile hydrolysis through amide/carboxylate stages produces the alpha-amino acid.", "reasoning": "Hydrolysis of the Strecker aminonitrile to isoleucine is the terminal step of the canonical prebiotic Strecker pathway and underlies the isoleucine detections in spark-discharge experiments and meteorite-parent-body chemistry (Miller, 1957; Ring et al., 1972; Pizzarello & Cronin, 2008)."}, {"id": "rxn_011", "name": "Biochemical/protometabolic formation of alpha-ketobutyrate from glyoxylate and pyruvate", "inputs": ["mol_011", "mol_012"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [null, null], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "true", "other": "nonenzymatic protometabolic alpha-keto-acid network in pools/mineral interfaces"}, "mechanism": "Carbon-carbon bond formation within alpha-keto-acid chemistry extends pyruvate/glyoxylate carbon skeletons to alpha-ketobutyrate.", "reasoning": "The research highlights alpha-ketobutyrate as a biologically central branch-point and notes that noncanonical routes from glyoxylate plus pyruvate exist in modern metabolism, which is prebiotically significant because both metabolites are plausible prebiotic intermediates. This exact prebiotic step remains unproven but is directly motivated by the supplied literature (Kim et al., 2020; Springsteen et al., 2018; speculative connector acknowledged)."}, {"id": "rxn_012", "name": "Biochemical/protometabolic condensation of alpha-ketobutyrate to alpha-keto-beta-methylvalerate", "inputs": ["mol_013", "mol_011"], "outputs": ["mol_014"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [null, null], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "true", "other": "alpha-keto-acid condensation in protometabolic network; unresolved nonenzymatic analogue of BCAA pathway"}, "mechanism": "An acetyl/pyruvate-derived carbon unit is added to alpha-ketobutyrate to generate the C6 branched alpha-keto acid precursor of isoleucine.", "reasoning": "The supplied report states that alpha-keto-beta-methylvalerate is the penultimate biological precursor and may be accessible by nonenzymatic aldol/alpha-keto-acid chemistry from alpha-ketobutyrate plus an acetyl equivalent, but this has not yet been demonstrated. It is included because reductive amination and Bucherer-Bergs routes to isoleucine depend on this precursor (Ter-Ovanessian et al., 2025; supplied report conclusion; explicitly speculative but necessary)."}, {"id": "rxn_013", "name": "Hydrothermal FeS-mediated reductive amination of alpha-keto-beta-methylvalerate to isoleucine", "inputs": ["mol_014", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["mackinawite (FeS)", "pyrite (FeS2)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "373K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "freshly precipitated FeS / FeS2 surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "anaerobic acidic-to-neutral primordial amino acid synthesis conditions"}, "mechanism": "The alpha-keto acid undergoes imine formation with ammonia followed by mineral-assisted reduction to the alpha-amino acid.", "reasoning": "Reductive amination of alpha-oxo acids with FeS was demonstrated for primordial amino acid synthesis and later revisited with freshly precipitated FeS or Fe(OH)2. The general chemistry is applicable to isoleucine if alpha-keto-beta-methylvalerate is available, but the precursor's prebiotic supply remains unresolved (Hafenbradl et al., 1995; Huber & Wachtershauser, 2003)."}, {"id": "rxn_014", "name": "Surface UV-photocatalytic amination of alpha-keto-beta-methylvalerate to isoleucine", "inputs": ["mol_014", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulf