: null, "aqueous": "true", "other": "extended hydrolysis during geothermal cycling"}, "mechanism": "Ring opening and hydrolysis of the hydantoin intermediate produce the alpha-amino acid isoleucine.", "reasoning": "This is the terminal step of Bucherer-Bergs chemistry. While direct isoleucine-specific experimental demonstration is not cited in the report, the reaction is presented as a general route for alpha-keto acids and therefore a justified extension to alpha-keto-beta-methylvalerate (Pulletikurti et al., 2022; speculative extension noted)."}, {"id": "rxn_017", "name": "Biochemical transamination analogue from alpha-keto-beta-methylvalerate to isoleucine", "inputs": ["mol_014", "mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [null, null], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "true", "other": "mineral-interface or pool chemistry, reductant available"}, "mechanism": "Amine transfer or reductive transamination analogue converts the alpha-keto acid directly to isoleucine.", "reasoning": "The supplied report treats reductive amination/transamination-style conversion of alpha-keto-beta-methylvalerate as the direct metabolic analogue to isoleucine biosynthesis. Nonenzymatic realization is less well established than FeS-mediated amination, so this is included as a weakly supported connector rather than a primary route (Hafenbradl et al., 1995; Huber & Wachtershauser, 2003; supplied report conclusion)."}], "pathways": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "name": "Canonical spark-Strecker isoleucine pathway", "description": "Volcanic discharge produces HCN/NH3 and branched aldehydes; 2-methylbutanal undergoes Strecker synthesis to aminonitrile, then hydrolysis to isoleucine.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_005", "rxn_008", "rxn_009", "rxn_010"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_003", "mol_008", "mol_009"]}, {"pathway_id": "P2", "name": "Hydrothermal acetaldehyde to crossed-aldol Strecker pathway", "description": 