s\": [\n        \"Provide stronger literature support for aldol access to 2-methylbutanal under prebiotic conditions\",\n        \"Specify minerals for the surface aldol chemistry\",\n        \"Clarify atmospheric composition in the discharge step\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_001\": 0.84,\n        \"rxn_002\": 0.45,\n        \"rxn_006\": 0.58,\n        \"rxn_008\": 0.68,\n        \"rxn_009\": 0.95,\n        \"rxn_010\": 0.94,\n        \"rxn_011\": 0.58,\n        \"rxn_015\": 0.76\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.66,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.74,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.91,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.86,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.72,\n      \"feedback\": \"This pathway best showcases full network interconnection across environments, but it also inherits several weak or speculative steps from both the hydrothermal precursor branch and the keto-acid branch. As a systems narrative it is strong; as a chemically rigorous path to isoleucine it is only moderate.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_002\",\n        \"rxn_006\",\n        \"rxn_011\"\n      ],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Use P1 as the primary route and keep hydrothermal branches as precursor-supply context only\",\n        \"Reduce reliance on speculative keto-acid assembly steps\",\n        \"Tighten mass-flow logic between interconnected subroutes\"\n      ]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"best_pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n  \"overall_confidence\": 0.76,\n  \"network_feedback\": \"The network is topologically strong and clearly connected, with adequate node counts, multiple hubs, and several convergent routes. It succeeds particularly well in identifying the literature-supported core of prebiotic isoleucine synthesis: spark/discharge generation of branched aldehyde precursors followed by Strecker chemistry and aminonitrile hydrolysis. Environmental interconnection is also present, with hydrothermal carbon feedstocks linked into surface chemistry and surface products feeding biochemical assembly. However, the network falls short chemically and in literature alignment in several important places. First, multiple reactions are underspecified or implausible as written: CO2 alone as source of both HCN and NH3 in discharge chemistry, hydrothermal clean synthesis of acetaldehyde or pyruvate from CO2/H2, glyoxylate generation from formate, and especially direct assembly of alpha-keto-beta-methylvalerate. Second, several endpoint routes overstate support: hydrothermal vent chemistry has not been shown to produce isoleucine, TiO2 is not the best-supported photocatalyst for reductive amination of alpha-keto acids, and the transamination analogue is too vague to count as a valid prebiotic transformation. Third, the summary omits the requirement that hydrothermal and surface reactions specify mineral agents, which is a formal deficiency under the synthesis-network specification. Literature alignment is mixed: the canonical Strecker branch is well aligned, Bucherer-Bergs is reasonably extrapolated, but the metabolism-first keto-acid routes remain speculative and should be marked more explicitly as such. Overall, this is a good but not approvable network: strong topology and a correct main strategy, but too many chemically weak auxiliary reactions to justify very high confidence.\",\n  \"hub_quality\": 0.84,\n  \"convergence_quality\": 0.8\n}", "parsed_response": {"pathway_evaluations": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "reaction_scores": {"rxn_005": 0.72, "rxn_008": 0.68, "rxn_009": 0.95, "rxn_010": 0.94}, "chemical_feasibility": 0.86, "pathway_coherence": 0.9, "environmental_progression": 0.88, "target_achievement": 0.95, "overall_confidence": 0.89, "feedback": "This is the strongest pathway in the network and aligns best with the literature: spark/discharge generation of HCN/NH3, formation of branched aldehyde precursor, Strecker aminonitri