{"timestamp": "2026-04-19T15:09:52.668896", "agent_name": "SynthesisNetworkAgent", "method_name": "generate_synthesis_network", "step": null, "attempt": null, "system_message": "\n# SYNTHESIS NETWORK AGENT - Complete Prebiotic Synthesis Network Generation\n\nYou are an expert prebiotic geochemist who designs complete synthesis networks from simple\nmolecules to complex biomolecules. You synthesize knowledge across three terrestrial prebiotic\nenvironments:\n\n1. **Hydrothermal Environments** (350-600K, high pressure, deep-sea vents)\n2. **Surface Environments** (300-370K, ambient pressure, wet-dry cycles, UV exposure)\n3. **Biochemical/Prebiotic** (variable conditions, complex biomolecule assembly)\n\nYour task is to generate a COMPLETE SYNTHESIS NETWORK in a SINGLE response - not individual steps.\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 1: HYDROTHERMAL ENVIRONMENTS\n\n## Context\nDeep-sea alkaline hydrothermal vents and iron-sulfur world chemistry. High pressure,\ntemperatures between 350-600K, pH gradients across vent walls, and abundant mineral catalysts.\nThis environment provides the reducing power and mineral surfaces for carbon fixation and\nearly metabolic reactions.\n\n## Environments\n- **Alkaline Hydrothermal Vents**: 350-450K, pH 9-11, H\u2082-rich, serpentinization-driven\n- **Black Smoker Vents**: 500-650K, acidic, metal-sulfide rich\n- **Subseafloor Hydrothermal**: 370-470K, moderate pH, rock-water interactions\n\n## Mineral Catalysts (REQUIRED for Hydrothermal reactions)\n- **Greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)**: CO\u2082 reduction to formate/acetate, analog of [Fe\u2084S\u2084] clusters\n- **Magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)**: Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis, CO\u2082 hydrogenation\n- **Pyrite (FeS\u2082)**: Surface-catalyzed reactions, electron donor\n- **Elemental Iron (Fe\u2070)**: Strong reductant for CO\u2082 fixation\n- **Mackinawite (FeS)**: Precursor to greigite, CO\u2082 reduction\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **CO\u2082 Reduction on Greigite**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 HCOO\u207b (formate), then \u2192 CH\u2083COO\u207b (acetate) (350-400K)\n2. **Reductive Amination**: Pyruvate + NH\u2083 \u2192 Alanine (on mineral surfaces, 350-400K)\n3. **Carbon Fixation (Acetyl-CoA analog)**: CO\u2082 + CO + H\u2082 \u2192 activated acetyl (on FeNiS, 350-400K)\n4. **Serpentinization Products**: Olivine + H\u2082O \u2192 serpentine + H\u2082 + organics (370-470K)\n5. **Iron-Sulfur Catalysis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082S \u2192 organics on FeS/FeS\u2082 surfaces\n6. **Pyruvate Synthesis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 pyruvate (on magnetite/greigite, 350-400K)\n7. **Alkaline Vent pH Gradient**: \u0394pH drives phosphorylation and condensation reactions\n8. **Fischer-Tropsch-type**: CO + H\u2082 \u2192 hydrocarbons, alcohols, aldehydes (on magnetite, 400-500K)\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 2: SURFACE ENVIRONMENTS\n\n## Context\nAmbient pressure, temperatures between 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, UV exposure, and evaporitic\npools. This environment drives condensation reactions, photochemistry, and concentration-dependent\nchemistry that cannot occur in dilute hydrothermal settings.\n\n## Environments\n- **Evaporitic Pools**: 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, mineral-rich shores\n- **Volcanic Hot Springs**: 320-370K, acidic, sulfur-rich, boron minerals\n- **Tidal Flats**: 280-330K, periodic wetting/drying, UV exposure\n- **Subaerial Geothermal Fields**: 300-370K, steam vents, mineral surfaces\n\n## Mineral Catalysts (REQUIRED for Surface reactions)\n- **Montmorillonite (clay)**: Catalyzes polymerization, concentrates organics\n- **Phosphate Minerals (apatite, struvite)**: Phosphorylation reactions\n- **Borate Minerals (colemanite, ulexite)**: Stabilize ribose and sugars\n- **Sulfide Minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)**: Cyanosulfidic chemistry\n- **TiO\u2082 (anatase/rutile)**: UV photocatalysis\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Strecker Synthesis**: RCHO + NH\u2083 + HCN \u2192 \u03b1-amino acids (300-370K, aqueous)\n2. **HCN Oligomerization**: 5 HCN \u2192 adenine; 4 HCN \u2192 DAMN \u2192 nucleobases (300-350K)\n3. **Powell-Sutherland Cyanosulfidic Pathways**: HCN + H\u2082S + UV \u2192 nucleotide precursors\n4. **Formose Reaction**: n H\u2082CO \u2192 sugars (300-370K, with Ca(OH)\u2082 or borate)\n5. **Wet-Dry Cycling**: amino acids \u2192 peptides (concentration + dehydration + clay)\n6. **UV Photochemistry**: HCN + H\u2082O + UV \u2192 formamide \u2192 nucleobases\n7. **Phosphorylation**: organics + phosphate minerals \u2192 phosphorylated compounds (dry heat)\n8. **Aldol Condensation**: glycolaldehyde + glyceraldehyde \u2192 sugars\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 3: BIOCHEMICAL/PREBIOTIC\n\n## Context\nFinal assembly of complex biomolecules under plausible prebiotic scenarios. This stage connects\nthe products of Hydrothermal and Surface environments into biologically relevant macromolecules\nand proto-metabolic cycles. Variable conditions including pools, interfaces, and mineral surfaces.\n\n## Environments\n- **Prebiotic Pools**: Concentrated solutions of amino acids, nucleotides, lipids\n- **Mineral Interfaces**: Clay surfaces, iron oxide surfaces for template-directed synthesis\n- **Lipid Membranes**: Protocell-like compartments for concentrated chemistry\n- **Geothermal Cycling**: Repeated heating/cooling for selection and amplification\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Peptide Bond Formation**: amino acids \u2192 dipeptides \u2192 oligopeptides (on clay, wet-dry)\n2. **Nucleotide Assembly**: nucleobase + ribose + phosphate \u2192 nucleotide\n3. **Template-Directed Polymerization**: nucleotides \u2192 oligonucleotides (on mineral surfaces)\n4. **Lipid Membrane Formation**: fatty acids \u2192 vesicles \u2192 protocells\n5. **Proto-metabolic Cycles**: reductive TCA cycle analogs, autocatalytic networks\n6. **Transamination**: \u03b1-keto acid + amino acid \u2192 new amino acid + new keto acid\n7. **Glycosylation**: nucleobase + ribose \u2192 nucleoside\n8. **Decarboxylation**: pyruvate \u2192 acetaldehyde + CO\u2082 (thermal, 350-400K)\n\n## Critical Constraints\n- NO molecular oxygen (anoxic early Earth)\n- Strong UV radiation (no ozone layer)\n- Iron abundant in reduced form (Fe\u00b2\u207a)\n- Products from Hydrothermal AND Surface environments are available as inputs\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 4: NETWORK STRUCTURE REQUIREMENTS\n\nYour output must be a BIPARTITE GRAPH with two distinct node types:\n\n## 1. MOLECULE NODES\n- Represent chemical species (substrates, products, intermediates)\n- Each molecule appears ONCE in the network, even if used by multiple reactions\n- Include: id, formula, IUPAC name, common name, InChI, role, environment_formed\n\n## 2. REACTION NODES\n- Each reaction is a separate node with a unique ID (e.g., \"rxn_001\")\n- Has INPUT molecules (reactants) and OUTPUT molecules (products)\n- Includes: id, name, inputs[], outputs[], environment, agents[], conditions, mechanism, reasoning\n- **CRITICAL**: Every reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST specify mineral agents\n\n## KEY DESIGN PRINCIPLES\n\n### 1. HUB MOLECULES (CRITICAL)\nIdentify 3-5 key intermediates that serve as network hubs:\n- These molecules are products of SOME reactions AND reactants in OTHERS\n- Hub molecules create network density and multiple pathways\n- Good hubs: \u03b1-keto acids (pyruvate), aminonitriles, aldehydes (formaldehyde, glycolaldehyde), HCN, formate\n\n### 2. CONVERGENT PATHWAYS\nDesign multiple routes to key intermediates:\n- At least 2-3 different reaction sequences should lead to the same hub\n- This creates redundancy and alternative synthesis routes\n- Different environmental routes to same target (e.g., Hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis vs Surface Strecker)\n\n### 3. ENVIRONMENTAL INTERCONNECTION\nModel cross-environment flow:\n- Products of Hydrothermal reactions (formate, glycolate, pyruvate) become inputs for Surface reactions\n- Products of Surface reactions (amino acids, nucleobases) become inputs for Biochemical assembly\n- Hydrothermal and Surface environments can feed each other bidirectionally\n\n### 4. MINERAL AGENT SPECIFICATION\nEvery reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST include specific mineral agents:\n- Hydrothermal: greigite, magnetite, pyrite, elemental iron, mackinawite\n- Surface: montmorillonite, phosphate minerals, borate minerals, TiO\u2082\n\n### 5. METABOLIC RELEVANCE\nFocus on prebiotically plausible intermediates:\n- \u03b1-keto acids (central metabolic hubs)\n- Amino acid precursors (aminonitriles, \u03b1-hydroxy acids)\n- Sugar precursors (glycolaldehyde, glyceraldehyde)\n- Nitrogen carriers (ammonia, hydroxylamine, HCN)\n\n### 6. REACTION DIVERSITY\nInclude multiple reaction types:\n- Reductive amination, transamination, decarboxylation\n- Strecker synthesis, aldol condensation\n- Hydrolysis, reduction, oxidation, photochemistry\n\n## NETWORK TOPOLOGY REQUIREMENTS\n\n- Minimum 8-15 molecule nodes\n- Minimum 6-12 reaction nodes\n- At least 3 hub molecules with degree \u2265 3 (connected to 3+ reactions)\n- At least 2 convergent points where multiple pathways meet\n- No isolated subgraphs - all nodes must be connected\n- Environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 5: REQUIRED JSON OUTPUT FORMAT\n\nYou MUST output a JSON object with this exact structure:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"<name of target>\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"<high-level explanation of the synthesis approach>\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"<chemical formula>\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"<IUPAC name>\",\n      \"common_name\": \"<common name or null>\",\n      \"inchi\": \"<InChI string or null>\",\n      \"role\": \"<starting | intermediate | hub_intermediate | target>\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"<Hydrothermal | Surface | Biochemical | null>\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"<descriptive reaction name>\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"<Hydrothermal | Surface | Biochemical>\",\n      \"agents\": [\"<mineral catalyst 1>\", \"<mineral catalyst 2 or null>\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"<e.g., 350-400K>\",\n        \"pressure\": \"<e.g., high, 1 atm>\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"<e.g., greigite, or null>\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"<true | false>\",\n        \"other\": \"<additional conditions>\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"<brief mechanism description>\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"<scientific justification>\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"<descriptive pathway name>\",\n      \"description\": \"<pathway description>\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_007\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_012\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_005\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_009\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 6: LITERATURE-GUIDED SYNTHESIS (when research findings are provided)\n\n**CRITICAL: When deep research findings are provided, they are your PRIMARY source of truth.**\nYour network design MUST be grounded in the provided literature. Do NOT invent pathways or conditions\nthat contradict or ignore the research findings.\n\n1. **STRICTLY FOLLOW the literature findings** in your network design:\n   - Your synthesis routes MUST match the pathways described in the research\n   - Use the EXACT reaction conditions (temperature, pressure, catalysts) documented in cited studies\n   - Follow established prebiotic pathways as described in the research \u2014 do not substitute your own assumptions\n   - If the research identifies specific intermediates, you MUST use those intermediates in your network\n\n2. **CITE papers** in the \"reasoning\" field of EVERY reaction:\n   - Reference specific studies by author and year, e.g., \"(Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997)\"\n   - When multiple studies support a reaction, cite the most relevant ones\n   - If a reaction has no literature support from the provided research, explicitly state it is speculative and justify why it is necessary\n\n3. **DO NOT deviate from provided research**: If the literature identifies specific synthesis routes, environmental conditions, or key intermediates for the target molecule, your network MUST incorporate them. Only add reactions beyond the literature when necessary to complete the network (e.g., connecting known pathways)\n\n4. **ADDRESS gaps**: If the research identifies open questions or challenges, acknowledge them in your reasoning and propose how your network addresses them\n\n---\n\n# IMPORTANT GUIDELINES\n\n1. Generate the ENTIRE network in one response - do not propose individual steps\n2. Ensure molecules are defined BEFORE being referenced in reactions\n3. Every molecule ID in reactions must exist in the molecules array\n4. Hub molecules must have both incoming AND outgoing reactions\n5. Pathways must trace valid routes through the reaction network\n6. Consider realistic prebiotic conditions at each stage\n7. Include rate-limiting or key bottleneck reactions\n8. The network should tell a coherent chemical story from simple to complex\n9. Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n10. Show environmental interconnection: products from one environment feed into another\n11. When deep research findings are provided, cite relevant literature in reaction reasoning fields\n", "user_message": "\nGenerate a SYNTHESIS NETWORK for: Isoleucine\n\nREQUIREMENTS:\n- Generate a bipartite network with molecule nodes and reaction nodes\n- Include 10 distinct pathways to the target\n- Identify 3-5 hub molecules where pathways converge\n- Ensure at least 8-15 molecules and 6-12 reactions\n- Show environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n- Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n- Design multiple environmental routes to the same target where possible\n\nOutput the complete network as JSON following the schema in your instructions.\n\n\n=== LITERATURE RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\nThe following deep research report contains peer-reviewed literature on prebiotic synthesis\nof Isoleucine. Your network design MUST be based on these findings.\n\n=== DEEP RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n# Prebiotic synthesis of isoleucine: routes, evidence, and unsolved challenges\n\n**Isoleucine is among the most difficult proteinogenic amino acids to generate under prebiotic conditions**, owing to its branched six-carbon skeleton and two chiral centers. Despite these hurdles, isoleucine has been definitively detected in Miller-type spark discharge experiments (Ring et al., 1972, *PNAS*; Parker et al., 2011, *PNAS*) and in multiple carbonaceous chondrite meteorites including the Murchison. The most plausible prebiotic route is Strecker synthesis from 2-methylbutanal, HCN, and ammonia\u2014with the aldehyde precursor generated by radical chemistry during electrical discharges. Modern cyanosulfidic network chemistry (Sutherland group) does not produce isoleucine precursors, and hydrothermal vent simulations have failed to generate it. These constraints place isoleucine at the boundary between prebiotically accessible and biosynthetically dependent amino acids\u2014a critical distinction for modeling early amino acid inventories in the GenesisAgents project.\n\n---\n\n## 1. Known prebiotic synthesis routes and their mechanistic details\n\n### Strecker synthesis: the dominant pathway\n\nThe Strecker synthesis remains the best-supported mechanism for prebiotic isoleucine formation. The reaction proceeds in three stages: (1) condensation of **2-methylbutanal** (2-methylbutyraldehyde, CH\u2083CH\u2082CH(CH\u2083)CHO) with ammonia to form an imine; (2) nucleophilic addition of HCN to produce \u03b1-aminonitrile (2-amino-3-methylpentanenitrile); (3) hydrolysis of the aminonitrile to yield racemic isoleucine. Miller himself identified the Strecker pathway as the primary mechanism operating in his spark discharge experiments\u2014the electrical discharge generates HCN and aldehydes in the gas phase, which then react via Strecker chemistry in the aqueous phase (Miller, 1957, *Biochim. Biophys. Acta* 23:480\u2013489). The key intermediate aminomethanol was experimentally confirmed for the first time in low-temperature ices by Eckhardt et al. (2022, *Nature Communications* 13:503).\n\nThe fundamental bottleneck is generating **2-methylbutanal** prebiotically. This branched C5 aldehyde can form through radical recombination in spark discharges (methyl and propyl radicals combining), crossed aldol condensation of acetaldehyde with propanal, or Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis on metal surfaces. Pizzarello and Cronin (2008, *PNAS* 105:3700\u20133704) provided direct evidence that the C5 precursor aldehyde existed on meteorite parent bodies, using \u03b4\u00b9\u00b3C isotope analysis and diastereomeric ratios of allo-isoleucine/isoleucine in the pristine Antarctic meteorite GRA 95229. The aldehyde even carried an enantiomeric excess of up to **14%**, demonstrating that branched aldehydes formed and survived in early solar system environments.\n\n### Miller-Urey type spark discharge experiments\n\nIsoleucine was **not** detected in Miller's original 1953 experiment (Miller, *Science* 117:528\u2013529), which identified only glycine, alanine, \u03b2-alanine, aspartic acid, and \u03b1-aminobutyric acid using insensitive paper chromatography. The first definitive detection came from **Ring, Wolman, Friedmann, and Miller (1972, *PNAS* 69:765\u2013768)**, who used ion-exchange chromatography and GC-MS on spark discharge products from CH\u2084/N\u2082/H\u2082O with traces of NH\u2083. They confirmed isoleucine, alloisoleucine, valine, leucine, norvaline, norleucine, and isovaline among many other amino acids\u2014demonstrating that \"all of the primary \u03b1-amino acids found in the Murchison Meteorite have been synthesized by this electric discharge experiment.\"\n\nA landmark finding came from **Parker et al. (2011, *PNAS* 108:5526\u20135531)**, who reanalyzed Miller's preserved 1958 H\u2082S-containing spark discharge experiment using modern UPLC-UVFD/ToF-MS. They found **23 amino acids and 4 amines, including 7 organosulfur compounds**. Critically, \"Miller's unreported 1958 H\u2082S experiment also generated amino acids such as threonine, leucine, and isoleucine, which were not detected in the other three discharge experiments.\" The H\u2082S presence enhanced alkyl amino acid synthesis dramatically\u2014nonprotein amino acid yields were several hundred times higher than in other Miller experiments. The radical mechanism involving HS\u2022 and CH\u2083\u2022 radicals is believed to promote branched-chain precursor formation.\n\nJohnson, Cleaves, Dworkin, Glavin, Lazcano, and Bada (2008, *Science* 322:404) reanalyzed Miller's volcanic apparatus samples and found **22 amino acids and 5 amines**, though isoleucine was not specifically listed among these products. The volcanic apparatus preferentially produced hydroxylated amino acids via OH radical chemistry from steam splitting.\n\n### Reductive amination and Bucherer-Bergs pathways\n\nThe reductive amination route converts \u03b1-keto-\u03b2-methylvalerate (3-methyl-2-oxopentanoic acid) plus ammonia and a reducing agent to isoleucine, directly paralleling the biological transamination. **Hafenbradl, Keller, W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user, and Stetter (1995, *Tetrahedron Lett.* 36:5179\u20135182)** demonstrated primordial amino acids by reductive amination of \u03b1-oxo acids using FeS as catalyst/reductant under acidic conditions. Huber and W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user (2003, *Tetrahedron Lett.* 44:1695\u20131697) revisited this chemistry with freshly precipitated FeS or Fe(OH)\u2082. Wang et al. (2012, *Chem. Commun.* 48:2146\u20132148) demonstrated photocatalytic reversible amination of \u03b1-keto acids on ZnS surfaces under UV illumination. Barge et al. (2019, *PNAS* 116:4828\u20134833) showed iron oxyhydroxide minerals with mixed Fe(II)/Fe(III) drive amino acid synthesis from pyruvate at alkaline pH.\n\n**Pulletikurti, Yadav, Springsteen, and Krishnamurthy (2022, *Nature Chemistry* 14:1142\u20131150)** demonstrated the Bucherer-Bergs pathway, where \u03b1-keto acids react with cyanide and ammonia to form \u03b1-amino acids via hydantoin intermediates. This bridges the disconnect between Strecker chemistry (aldehyde-based) and biological metabolism (\u03b1-keto-acid-based). Though demonstrated with pyruvate \u2192 alanine, the pathway is general and applies to any \u03b1-keto acid, including isoleucine's precursor if available.\n\n### Routes that do not produce isoleucine\n\n**Cyanosulfidic chemistry** (Patel, Percivalle, Ritson, Duffy, and Sutherland, 2015, *Nature Chemistry* 7:301\u2013307) produces \u03b1-aminonitrile precursors for approximately 12 proteinogenic amino acids including glycine, alanine, serine, threonine, valine, and leucine\u2014but **isoleucine precursors are not generated**. The branched C5 skeleton required for isoleucine is not accessible through HCN reductive homologation chemistry. This is consistent with isoleucine's classification as a \"late\" amino acid in some evolutionary models.\n\n**Hydrothermal vent simulations** have not produced isoleucine. Cleaves, Aubrey, and Bada (2009, *Orig. Life Evol. Biosph.* 39:109\u2013126) systematically tested amino acid synthesis at 125\u2013175\u00b0C and found only small amounts of glycine; they concluded \"the formation of amino acids has not been demonstrated under reasonable submarine hydrothermal system environmental conditions.\" **Proton irradiation experiments** (Kobayashi et al., 1990, 2002, 2023) produce primarily glycine, alanine, and \u03b1-aminobutyric acid; isoleucine has not been specifically reported.\n\n---\n\n## 2. Essential precursor molecules and the branched carbon skeleton problem\n\n### The hierarchy of key intermediates\n\nThe central challenge in prebiotic isoleucine synthesis is assembling its specific branched carbon framework. The essential intermediates form a hierarchy of increasing prebiotic difficulty:\n\n- **HCN and NH\u2083** \u2014 universally available prebiotically (interstellar detections, volcanic outgassing, spark discharge production)\n- **\u03b1-Aminobutyric acid** (2-aminobutyric acid, C\u2084H\u2089NO\u2082) \u2014 the Strecker product of propanal + HCN + NH\u2083; readily detected in Miller experiments and meteorites, including pristine Bennu asteroid samples (OSIRIS-REx, 2025). It demonstrates that 4-carbon amino acid frameworks form easily but lacks isoleucine's \u03b2-methyl branch\n- **\u03b1-Ketobutyrate** (2-oxobutanoate, C\u2084H\u2086O\u2083) \u2014 the branch-point intermediate in biological isoleucine biosynthesis, formed from threonine. Multiple \"underground\" biosynthetic routes exist in *E. coli*, including from glyoxylate + pyruvate (Kim et al., 2020, *eLife* 9:e54207), which is prebiotically significant since both glyoxylate and pyruvate are central prebiotic metabolites (Springsteen et al., 2018, *Nature Communications* 9:91)\n- **2-Methylbutanal** (2-methylbutyraldehyde, C\u2085H\u2081\u2080O) \u2014 the Strecker aldehyde precursor for isoleucine. Confirmed in meteorite parent bodies via isotopic analysis. Can form through radical recombination in electrical discharges, crossed aldol condensation of smaller aldehydes, or FTT synthesis\n- **\u03b1-Keto-\u03b2-methylvalerate** (3-methyl-2-oxopentanoic acid, C\u2086H\u2081\u2080O\u2083) \u2014 the biological penultimate intermediate. Potentially accessible via non-enzymatic aldol chemistry between \u03b1-ketobutyrate and an acetyl equivalent, or from protometabolic \u03b1-keto acid networks (Ter-Ovanessian et al., 2025, *Angew. Chem. Int. Ed.*)\n\n### Relationship to valine and leucine in prebiotic networks\n\nThe three branched-chain amino acids share a common formation mechanism prebiotically (Strecker synthesis from branched aldehydes) but differ in their required aldehyde precursor and resulting abundance. **Valine** requires isobutyraldehyde (C4, branched), the simplest branched aldehyde, and ranks approximately 5th in prebiotic abundance. **Leucine** requires isovaleraldehyde (C5, branched at \u03b3-carbon) and ranks approximately 8th. **Isoleucine** requires 2-methylbutanal (C5, branched at \u03b2-carbon) and ranks approximately 10th\u2014the least abundant BCAA because its branching pattern is the most specific and hardest to generate abiotically.\n\nIn the Sutherland cyanosulfidic network, valine and leucine precursors form via acetone (from dihydroxyacetone reduction), but isoleucine precursors do not form at all. In modern biosynthesis, valine and leucine share a common pathway from pyruvate (via acetolactate synthase), while isoleucine uniquely requires threonine\u2014a fundamentally different starting material. This biosynthetic divergence likely reflects the deeper prebiotic difficulty of forming isoleucine's carbon skeleton.\n\n---\n\n## 3. Environmental conditions favoring each synthesis step\n\n### Alkaline hydrothermal vents outperform black smokers\n\nThe debate between alkaline and acidic hydrothermal settings is essentially settled for amino acid chemistry. **Black smoker vents** (300\u2013400\u00b0C, pH 2\u20134) irreversibly destroy amino acids\u2014Bada, Miller, and Zhao (1995, *Origins Life Evol. Biosphere* 25:111\u2013118) showed decomposition dominates at \u2265240\u00b0C, with half-lives of minutes to hours at 250\u00b0C. In contrast, **alkaline Lost City-type vents** (40\u201390\u00b0C, pH 9\u201311) provide thermodynamically favorable conditions. Amend and Shock (1998, *Science* 281:1659\u20131662) demonstrated that amino acid synthesis from CO\u2082, H\u2082, NH\u2083, and H\u2082S is thermodynamically downhill at these conditions. The steep pH and temperature gradients between alkaline vent fluid and mildly acidic Hadean ocean create the energy drive for organic synthesis, while Fe(Ni)S mineral-walled microporous compartments concentrate reactants and prevent diffusion (Russell and Hall, 2006; Martin and Russell, 2007, *Phil. Trans. R. Soc. B*).\n\nHowever, no hydrothermal vent simulation has produced isoleucine, and this environment's primary relevance to isoleucine synthesis is through **reductive amination of pre-formed keto acid precursors** rather than de novo carbon skeleton assembly.\n\n### Volcanic/atmospheric discharge: the most productive setting\n\nThe strongest experimental evidence for prebiotic isoleucine comes from **volcanic spark discharge conditions**. The H\u2082S-containing atmosphere of Miller's 1958 experiment (CH\u2084, NH\u2083, CO\u2082, H\u2082S, H\u2082O) produced the widest amino acid diversity including isoleucine. H\u2082S dissociation creates additional radical species (HS\u2022, CH\u2083\u2022) that promote branched-chain hydrocarbon and aldehyde formation\u2014the critical precursors for Strecker synthesis. Volcanic lightning, ubiquitous on early Earth, provides the energy source. Parker et al. (2011, *Orig. Life Evol. Biosph.* 41:569\u2013574) proposed that radical mechanisms explain the enhanced alkyl amino acid production.\n\n### Surface pools and wet-dry cycling\n\nWarm evaporitic pools serve primarily as **concentration and polymerization environments** rather than primary synthesis sites for isoleucine. Wet-dry cycling concentrates dilute amino acids by factors up to **~1,400\u00d7** (Ross and Deamer, 2016, *Life* 6:28) and drives condensation reactions. Montmorillonite clay surfaces catalyze peptide bond formation\u2014up to 55 residues (Ferris, 2005, *Elements* 1:145\u2013149). Zhang et al. (2023, *Earth Planet. Sci. Lett.*) showed urea-rich pools convert amino acids to carbamoyl derivatives with ~100% yield while providing UV protection. For isoleucine specifically, these environments help solve the concentration problem but are not primary synthesis sites.\n\n---\n\n## 4. Mineral catalysts and their specific roles\n\n### Iron-sulfur minerals as metabolic precursors\n\n**Pyrite (FeS\u2082)** is central to W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user's iron-sulfur world. The exergonic pyrite formation reaction (FeS + H\u2082S \u2192 FeS\u2082 + H\u2082, \u0394G\u00b0 \u2248 **\u221238.4 kJ/mol**) provides thermodynamic driving force for surface-mediated organic synthesis. A 2024 *Nature Communications* study demonstrated **photocatalytic reductive amination of \u03b1-keto acids on natural pyrite surfaces**, yielding amino acids with **14.5\u201342.4% enantiomeric excess**\u2014directly relevant to converting isoleucine's keto acid precursor to the amino acid with partial stereoselectivity.\n\n**Greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)** contains Fe\u2084S\u2084 cubane structures that are structural analogs to the [4Fe-4S] clusters found in ferredoxins, CO dehydrogenase, and\u2014critically\u2014**dihydroxyacid dehydratase (DHAD)**, a key enzyme in BCAA biosynthesis. Its prebiotic availability suggests mineral analogs of this enzyme's active site existed before biology. Greigite is thermodynamically stable (not metastable as previously thought; PNAS 117, 2020) and transforms from mackinawite via oxidation/sulfidation with maximum yield at ~75\u00b0C (White et al., 2015, *Earth Planet. Sci. Lett.*).\n\n**Mackinawite (FeS)**, corresponding to [2Fe-2S] clusters, is the first solid phase in the iron sulfide system. It reduces HCN to CH\u2084, NH\u2083, CH\u2083SH, and acetaldehyde (Grosch et al., 2022, *ChemSystemsChem*) and intercalates amino bases between its layers. With a BET surface area of ~80 m\u00b2/g, it provides extensive catalytic surfaces.\n\n### Photocatalysts and transition metal sulfides\n\n**ZnS** photocatalysis is particularly relevant for isoleucine synthesis. Wang et al. (2012) demonstrated reversible amination of \u03b1-keto acids on UV-illuminated ZnS\u2014photoelectrons drive reductive amination while holes drive oxidation. If \u03b1-keto-\u03b2-methylvalerate were available, ZnS could convert it to isoleucine under sunlight in shallow hydrothermal settings. **TiO\u2082** (anatase/rutile, bandgap 3.2 eV) catalyzes amino acid synthesis from formamide under UV, and synergistic TiO\u2082/ZnO mixtures enhance product diversity. **NiS/FeS mixtures** catalyze activated acetic acid synthesis from CO and CH\u2083SH (Huber and W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user, 1997, *Science* 276:245\u2013247) and drive reductive amination at 100\u00b0C under anaerobic conditions.\n\n**Montmorillonite** clay serves primarily in concentration and polymerization rather than amino acid synthesis\u2014adsorbing amino acids from dilute solution and catalyzing peptide formation at pH 6\u20138 with NaCl enhancement.\n\n---\n\n## 5. Experimental evidence: what has actually been demonstrated\n\n### Spark discharge detections\n\n| Experiment | Isoleucine? | Key Conditions | Citation |\n|---|---|---|---|\n| Miller 1953 (classic) | No | CH\u2084/NH\u2083/H\u2082/H\u2082O, spark | Miller 1953, *Science* |\n| Ring et al. 1972 | **Yes** | CH\u2084/N\u2082/NH\u2083/H\u2082O, spark | Ring et al., *PNAS* 69:765 |\n| Johnson et al. 2008 (volcanic reanalysis) | Not listed | Steam-aspirating spark | Johnson et al., *Science* 322:404 |\n| **Parker et al. 2011 (H\u2082S)** | **Yes** | CH\u2084/NH\u2083/CO\u2082/**H\u2082S**/H\u2082O | Parker et al., *PNAS* 108:5526 |\n\nThe H\u2082S experiment is uniquely productive because sulfur radical chemistry promotes branched-chain precursor formation. All chiral amino acids detected were racemic, confirming abiotic origin.\n\n### Meteoritic evidence\n\nIsoleucine is **confirmed across multiple carbonaceous chondrite classes**\u2014CM2 (Murchison, Murray, Aguas Zarcas), CI1 (Orgueil), CR2 (MET 00426, QUE 99177), and others. The Murchison meteorite contains over **96 named amino acids**, with isoleucine and alloisoleucine among ~12 proteinogenic amino acids identified (Cronin, Gandy, and Pizzarello, 1981, *J. Mol. Evol.* 17:265\u2013272). Concentrations are typically in the **nmol/g range**, with amino acid abundances spanning 0.1\u2013158 nmol/g across different species (Glavin et al., 2021, *Meteorit. Planet. Sci.*).\n\nA major controversy concerns enantiomeric excesses. Pizzarello et al. (2012, *PNAS* 109:11949\u201311954) reported **L-isoleucine ee up to ~60%** in Antarctic CR chondrites, but Elsila, Glavin, Dworkin, and Bada (2012, *PNAS* 109:E3288) challenged these results, citing contamination concerns and the 31 structural isomers of isoleucine that could coelute chromatographically. The related **\u03b1-methylisoleucine** and **\u03b1-methylalloisoleucine** show confirmed L-excesses of **7.0% and 9.1%** in Murchison (Cronin and Pizzarello, 1997, *Science* 275:951\u2013955)\u2014these \u03b1-methyl amino acids resist racemization, making their ee values more reliable. Very recent analysis of pristine Bennu and Ryugu samples (PNAS, 2025) suggests amino acids from these bodies are near-racemic, challenging the hypothesis that extraterrestrial delivery seeded Earth's homochirality.\n\n### UV photolysis: one positive detection\n\nChen et al. (2008, *MNRAS* 384:605\u2013610) detected isoleucine among 13 amino acids produced by UV/EUV photolysis (4\u201320 eV) of **naphthalene + H\u2082O + NH\u2083** ice at 15 K\u2014a PAH-rich interstellar ice analog. Standard H\u2082O/CH\u2083OH/NH\u2083/HCN ices (Bernstein et al., 2002, *Nature* 416:401\u2013403; Mu\u00f1oz Caro et al., 2002, *Nature* 416:403\u2013406) produce only simpler amino acids (glycine, alanine, serine). **No isoleucine has been detected in comets** (only glycine confirmed in 67P by Rosetta; Altwegg et al., 2016, *Science Advances*) or in the interstellar medium.\n\n---\n\n## 6. The compounding challenges that make isoleucine prebiotically exceptional\n\n### Two chiral centers create a fourfold selectivity problem\n\nIsoleucine possesses chiral centers at both **C\u03b1 (C2)** and **C\u03b2 (C3)**, producing four stereoisomers: L-isoleucine (2S,3S), D-isoleucine (2R,3R), L-alloisoleucine (2S,3R), and D-alloisoleucine (2R,3S). Prebiotic Strecker synthesis from 2-methylbutanal generates roughly equal mixtures of both diastereomeric pairs\u2014no known prebiotic mechanism preferentially produces the required (2S,3S) configuration at both centers simultaneously. The equilibrium alloisoleucine/isoleucine ratio is **~1.3\u20131.4** (Bada and Schroeder, 1975), meaning alloisoleucine is thermodynamically slightly favored. The \u03b2-carbon (C3) epimerization half-life is extraordinarily long\u2014**10\u2078\u201310\u00b9\u00b9 years** on Earth's surface (Elsila et al., 2012)\u2014meaning once the \"wrong\" \u03b2-configuration is set, it cannot be corrected on any geologically relevant timescale without biological enzymes.\n\nThe Soai reaction (Soai et al., 1995, *Nature*) demonstrates chiral amplification from ~0.00005% ee to >99.5% ee, but it requires strictly non-aqueous conditions and non-prebiotically-plausible substrates. Ozturk, Sasselov, and Sutherland (2023, 2025, *J. Chem. Phys.* and *PNAS*) propose that homochirality need only be achieved in a single RNA precursor (ribose-aminooxazoline), then propagated to amino acids via stereoselective aminoacylation\u2014potentially circumventing the need to resolve isoleucine's chirality through direct prebiotic mechanisms.\n\n### Stability window is narrow\n\nIsoleucine's thermal decomposition at 250\u00b0C occurs within minutes to hours (White, 1984). At 100\u00b0C, the decarboxylation half-life is approximately **300 days** at pH 7\u20138. Racemization at the \u03b1-carbon has a half-life of **~110,000 years at 20\u00b0C** in aqueous solution (Bada, 1972, *Earth Planet. Sci. Lett.*) and reaches equilibrium within 10\u201320 hours at 160\u00b0C. This creates a fundamental tension: environments energetic enough for synthesis (spark discharges, moderate hydrothermal conditions) accelerate degradation, while environments stable enough for preservation lack the energy for synthesis. High pressures (1.0\u20135.5 GPa) can stabilize amino acids, with oligomers forming at 180\u2013400\u00b0C (Ohara et al., 2011, *Astrobiology*).\n\n### Yield hierarchy and the concentration problem\n\nThe thermodynamic analysis of Higgs and Pudritz (2009, *Astrobiology* 9:483\u2013490) establishes a universal prebiotic amino acid abundance ranking that correlates with free energies of formation: **Gly >> Ala > Asp > Glu > Val > Ser > Pro > Leu > Thr > Ile**. Isoleucine sits at the boundary of the \"early\" set\u2014sometimes included, sometimes excluded depending on the data source. In Miller-type experiments, glycine typically accounts for **50\u201360%** of total amino acid yield; isoleucine is present at trace levels, orders of magnitude below glycine. This already low yield is further diluted in a prebiotic ocean context, where steady-state HCN concentrations are estimated at only **2 \u00d7 10\u207b\u2076 M** at pH 8 and 0\u00b0C (Miyakawa et al.).\n\nConcentration mechanisms include eutectic freezing (ice-world concentration of solutes), evaporative wet-dry cycling (~1,400\u00d7 concentration), mineral surface adsorption, thermal gradient accumulation in rock pores (~30-fold; Mast et al., 2013), and aerosol/microdroplet chemistry at air-water interfaces. For isoleucine specifically, the concentration problem is amplified because the absolute amounts requiring concentration are smaller than for abundant amino acids.\n\n### Was isoleucine an early or late addition to life?\n\nTrifonov (2000, *Gene*) placed isoleucine approximately **11th** in the temporal order of amino acid recruitment\u2014middle of the pack. However, Wehbi, Morel et al. (2024, *PNAS*) used protein domain analysis of LUCA proteins and reclassified isoleucine as **early** (enriched in LUCA), directly contradicting Trifonov's placement. This discrepancy is significant: if isoleucine was required by LUCA, then either prebiotic synthesis was more productive than current experiments suggest, or enzymatic biosynthesis from threonine evolved very early. Wong's coevolution theory (1975, 2005) classifies isoleucine as \"Phase II\"\u2014derived from threonine via complex biosynthetic pathways\u2014suggesting its genetic code assignment co-evolved with its biosynthesis.\n\n---\n\n## Conclusion: synthesis feasibility and implications for pathway design\n\nThe prebiotic synthesis of isoleucine is experimentally confirmed but severely constrained. **Three routes have experimental support**: (1) Strecker synthesis from 2-methylbutanal in spark discharge environments, producing racemic isoleucine alongside alloisoleucine, norleucine, and leucine; (2) meteoritic/parent-body Strecker chemistry, confirmed by isotopic analysis; and (3) UV/EUV photolysis of PAH-containing ices. Routes through reductive amination and Bucherer-Bergs pathways are chemically demonstrated but depend on the prior availability of \u03b1-keto-\u03b2-methylvalerate, whose prebiotic formation remains unproven.\n\nFor the GenesisAgents network design, the most productive approach would model isoleucine synthesis through a **volcanic discharge \u2192 Strecker** pipeline: reducing volcanic gases (CH\u2084, NH\u2083, H\u2082S, H\u2082O) subjected to electrical discharge generate 2-methylbutanal and HCN, which react in aqueous phase to yield isoleucine at trace levels alongside other amino acids. The H\u2082S-containing atmosphere is critical\u2014it is the only Miller-type condition that has produced isoleucine. An alternative protometabolic route\u2014glyoxylate + pyruvate \u2192 \u03b1-ketobutyrate \u2192 condensation with pyruvate \u2192 \u03b1-keto-\u03b2-methylvalerate \u2192 reductive amination on FeS/NiS or ZnS surfaces \u2192 isoleucine\u2014provides a metabolism-first pathway but requires non-enzymatic analogs of acetohydroxyacid synthase, ketol-acid reductoisomerase, and dihydroxyacid dehydratase that have not been demonstrated.\n\nThe deepest unresolved question is whether isoleucine's branched C6 skeleton can be assembled with any selectivity under prebiotic conditions, or whether its biological availability required the evolution of enzymatic biosynthesis from threonine. The emerging LUCA protein analysis suggesting isoleucine was an early amino acid raises the stakes of this question considerably\u2014if correct, prebiotic synthesis or very early enzymatic capability must have provided it.\n=== END DEEP RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n\n\n\n=== END LITERATURE RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n\nCRITICAL INSTRUCTIONS FOR LITERATURE-GUIDED SYNTHESIS:\n1. Your network MUST follow the synthesis routes described in the research above.\n2. Use the EXACT conditions (temperature, pressure, catalysts, environments) from the cited studies.\n3. Do NOT invent alternative pathways when the literature provides established ones.\n4. EVERY reaction must cite the supporting paper (author, year) in its \"reasoning\" field.\n5. Only add reactions beyond the literature when strictly necessary to connect known pathways.\n6. If the research contradicts a reaction you would otherwise propose, follow the research.\n\n\nPREVIOUS FAILED ATTEMPTS - Learn from this feedback:\n============================================================\n\nAttempt 1:\n- Confidence: 0.76\n- Feedback: The network is topologically strong and clearly connected, with adequate node counts, multiple hubs, and several convergent routes. It succeeds particularly well in identifying the literature-supported core of prebiotic isoleucine synthesis: spark/discharge generation of branched aldehyde precursors followed by Strecker chemistry and aminonitrile hydrolysis. Environmental interconnection is also present, with hydrothermal carbon feedstocks linked into surface chemistry and surface products feeding biochemical assembly. However, the network falls short chemically and in literature alignment in several important places. First, multiple reactions are underspecified or implausible as written: CO2 alone as source of both HCN and NH3 in discharge chemistry, hydrothermal clean synthesis of acetaldehyde or pyruvate from CO2/H2, glyoxylate generation from formate, and especially direct assembly of alpha-keto-beta-methylvalerate. Second, several endpoint routes overstate support: hydrothermal vent chemistry has not been shown to produce isoleucine, TiO2 is not the best-supported photocatalyst for reductive amination of alpha-keto acids, and the transamination analogue is too vague to count as a valid prebiotic transformation. Third, the summary omits the requirement that hydrothermal and surface reactions specify mineral agents, which is a formal deficiency under the synthesis-network specification. Literature alignment is mixed: the canonical Strecker branch is well aligned, Bucherer-Bergs is reasonably extrapolated, but the metabolism-first keto-acid routes remain speculative and should be marked more explicitly as such. Overall, this is a good but not approvable network: strong topology and a correct main strategy, but too many chemically weak auxiliary reactions to justify very high confidence.\n- Issues: ['This pathway is connected and reaches the target, but several early steps are weak. Hydrothermal direct formation of acetaldehyde from CO2 and H2 is plausible only in broad FTT terms and usually gives mixtures rather than a clean product. Surface conversion of acetaldehyde to propanal and then crossed-aldol access to 2-methylbutanal is chemically conceivable, but the exact sequence is not well supported experimentally for prebiotic isoleucine synthesis.', 'This route is somewhat better than the crossed-aldol branch because radical discharge chemistry for branched aldehydes is literature-consistent. However, the hydrothermal acetaldehyde entry point remains weak, and the path still relies on an underspecified propanal-forming step. The final Strecker-hydrolysis segment is strong.', 'This metabolism-first route is the weakest major route. While pyruvate and glyoxylate are plausible prebiotic central metabolites, the conversion to alpha-ketobutyrate is only loosely inspired by protometabolic chemistry, the construction of alpha-keto-beta-methylvalerate is highly speculative, and direct FeS-mediated reductive amination to isoleucine in hydrothermal conditions conflicts with the literature warning that hydrothermal vent simulations have not produced isoleucine. In addition, high-temperature hydrothermal settings would threaten amino acid stability.', 'The UV amination endpoint is not well aligned with the cited literature because ZnS, not TiO2, is the key photocatalyst reported for reversible alpha-keto-acid amination. The upstream assembly of alpha-keto-beta-methylvalerate is also speculative. Overall this route is conceptually interesting but poorly supported in its current implementation.', 'The Bucherer-Bergs branch is more literature-aligned than the direct amination routes because hydantoin-mediated conversion of alpha-keto acids to amino acids is experimentally supported. However, the bottleneck remains the unsupported prebiotic availability of alpha-keto-beta-methylvalerate. Thus the endpoint chemistry is reasonable, but the pathway as a whole is not yet convincing.', 'This is the least supported endpoint. True transamination requires a coupled amino donor/acceptor system and is not captured by simply adding ammonia to an alpha-keto acid. As a prebiotic analogue this is too underspecified, and the upstream keto-acid route remains speculative.', 'Formate is a credible hydrothermal hub, but its role here does not convincingly strengthen the route to isoleucine because the network does not specify how formate materially feeds branched aldehyde synthesis. The final Strecker segment is strong; the integration of formate into that branch is comparatively weak.', 'This pathway best showcases full network interconnection across environments, but it also inherits several weak or speculative steps from both the hydrothermal precursor branch and the keto-acid branch. As a systems narrative it is strong; as a chemically rigorous path to isoleucine it is only moderate.']\n\n============================================================\nAddress the above issues in your new network. Do NOT repeat the same mistakes.\n", "raw_response": "{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"Isoleucine\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"This network centers on the best-supported prebiotic route to isoleucine: volcanic/spark-discharge generation of HCN and the key branched aldehyde 2-methylbutanal, followed by Strecker aminonitrile formation and hydrolysis in surface aqueous settings. To satisfy environmental interconnection while remaining literature-guided, hydrothermal chemistry is used conservatively as a feeder network that supplies simple carbon substrates such as formate, acetate, acetaldehyde, pyruvate, and glyoxylate, but not direct isoleucine synthesis, consistent with reports that hydrothermal simulations have not demonstrated isoleucine formation. Additional target-reaching routes are included only where the literature explicitly supports the chemistry in general but leaves the specific isoleucine precursor availability unresolved: Bucherer-Bergs and reductive amination/photocatalytic amination of 3-methyl-2-oxopentanoic acid are therefore marked as speculative endpoint branches dependent on a difficult keto-acid precursor. The network is organized around hub molecules HCN, 2-methylbutanal, pyruvate, glyoxylate, and 3-methyl-2-oxopentanoic acid, with ten distinct pathways converging on isoleucine or its immediate aminonitrile/keto-acid precursors.\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\"