rothermal isoleucine formation.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal pyruvate formation on iron-sulfur minerals\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\", \"greigite (Fe3S4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite/greigite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline vent redox gradients, anoxic\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Stepwise mineral-catalyzed CO2 reduction and C-C assembly yields alpha-keto acids such as pyruvate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Pyruvate is a central protometabolic alpha-keto acid often invoked in hydrothermal Fe-mineral chemistry and later reductive amination studies; here it is used as a realistic hub feeding speculative keto-acid branches rather than as evidence for vent isoleucine synthesis (Barge et al., 2019; Springsteen et al., 2018).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"Spark-discharge generation of HCN and ammonia from reducing volcanic gases\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_003\", \"mol_004\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"mineral-rich volcanic aerosols and UV-active surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"electrical discharge in CH4/NH3/CO2/H2S/H2O or CH4/N2/NH3/H2O atmospheres; post-discharge trapping in water\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Electrical discharge forms reactive radicals and nitriles in the gas phase, which dissolve into aqueous surface reservoirs.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"HCN and ammonia generation is foundatio