"Hydrothermal CO2 reduction to formate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\n        \"mol_001\",\n        \"mol_002\"\n      ],\n      \"outputs\": [\n        \"mol_005\"\n      ],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\n        \"greigite (Fe3S4)\",\n        \"mackinawite (FeS)\"\n      ],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite/mackinawite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline vent-like, anoxic, H2-rich\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Mineral-surface reduction of CO2 by H2 to C1 reduced carbon on iron-sulfur phases.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"FeS-family minerals and greigite are widely invoked for vent CO2 reduction to formate and related C1 products in alkaline hydrothermal settings; this provides a conservative hydrothermal carbon feedstock, not a direct isoleucine step (Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997; Russell & Hall, 2006; Martin & Russell, 2007).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_002\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal/FTT generation of acetaldehyde from reduced carbon feedstocks\",\n      \"inputs\": [\n        \"mol_001\",\n        \"mol_002\"\n      ],\n      \"outputs\": [\n        \"mol_006\"\n      ],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\n        \"magnetite (Fe3O4)\",\n        \"elemental iron (Fe0)\"\n      ],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"400-500K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite/Fe0\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"Fischer-Tropsch-type, anoxic, product mixture expected\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Fischer-Tropsch-type reduction of carbon oxides generates mixed low-molecular-weight aldehydes including acetaldehyde.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The literature report notes Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis on metal surfaces as a plausible source of branched aldehyde precursors, but not clean selective access to isoleucine precursors; accordingly this node is treated as a mixed-feed precursor source only (Pizzarello & Cronin, 2008; Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal pyruvate formation from CO2/H2\",\n      \"inputs\": [\n        \"mol_001\",\n        \"mol_002\"\n      ],\n      \"outputs\": [\n        \"mol_011\"\n      ],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\n        \"magnetite (Fe3O4)\",\n        \"greigite (Fe3S4)\"\n      ],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-400K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite/greigite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline vent analog; low-yield protometabolic alpha-keto acid chemistry\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Mineral-mediated multicarbon fixation producing alpha-keto acid intermediates.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Pyruvate is commonly treated as a plausible central prebiotic metabolite and is specifically highlighted in the research as a relevant feeder to underground biosynthetic analogs, but not as a demonstrated direct route to isoleucine in vents; therefore this step is used only as network support (Springsteen et al., 2018; Barge et al., 2019).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface spark-discharge production of HCN from reduced volcanic gases\",\n      \"inputs\": [\n        \"mol_003\"\n      ],\n      \"outputs\": [\n        \"mol_004\"\n      ],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\n        \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\",\n        \"sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)\"\n      ],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2 and sulfide mineral surfaces as collection/photochemical interfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"electrical discharge in CH4/NH3/CO2/H2S/H2O or CH4/N2/NH3/H2O atmospheres; volcanic lightning; anoxic\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Atmospheric discharge generates cyanide that is trapped into surface waters and mineral films.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"HCN is a core product of Miller-type discharge chemistry and the Strecker mechanism identified by Miller as the dominant amino acid-forming route; Parker et al. showed H2S-rich volcanic discharge conditions strongly expand amino acid diversity including isoleucine (Miller, 1957; Ring et al., 1972; Parker et al., 2011).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface spark-discharge/radical formation of 2-methylbutanal\",\n      \"inputs\": [\n        \"mol_006\",\n        \"mol_004\"\n      ],\n      \"outputs\": [\n        \"mol_007\"\n      ],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\n        \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\",\n        \"sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)\"\n      ],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2 and sulfide mineral surfaces as radical/photochemical interfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"volcanic spark-discharge, H2S-enhanced radical chemistry; branched aldehydes formed in complex mixtures\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Electrical discharge and sulfur-radical chemistry generate branched hydrocarbon/aldehyde mixtures including 2-methylbutanal through radical recombination chemistry.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The deep research identifies prebiotic generation of 2-methylbutanal as the key bottleneck and specifically points to radical chemistry in spark discharges, especially under H2S-containing conditions, as the best-supported terrestrial source. This step is intentionally broad and mixture-based rather than over-specified because selectivity is unresolved (Ring et al., 1972; Parker et al., 2011; Pizzarello & Cronin, 2008).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface Strecker synthesis of isoleucine aminonitrile from 2-methylbutanal\",\n      \"inputs\": [\n        \"mol_007\",\n        \"mol_003\",\n        \"mol_004\"\n      ],\n      \"outputs\": [\n        \"mol_008\"\n      ],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\n        \"sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)\",\n        \"montmorillonite\"\n      ],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"mineral concentration surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"imine formation followed by cyanide addition in aqueous surface pools\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"2-Methylbutanal condenses with ammonia to an imine, followed by nucleophilic cyanide addition to form the aminonitrile.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This is the dominant literature-supported route to prebiotic isoleucine. Strecker chemistry from 2-methylbutanal, NH3, and HCN is explicitly identified as the best-supported mechanism for isoleucine formation in discharge experiments and extraterrestrial parent-body chemistry (Miller, 1957; Ring et al., 1972; Parker et al., 2011; Pizzarello & Cronin, 2008).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface hydrolysis of isoleucine aminonitrile to racemic isoleucine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\n        \"mol_008\"\n      ],\n      \"outputs\": [\n        \"mol_009\"\n      ],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\n        \"montmorillonite\",\n        \"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\"\n      ],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"mineral-assisted aqueous hydrolysis\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"wet-dry cycling or standing aqueous pools; racemic and diastereomeric products expected\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Nitrile hydrolysis proceeds through amide/carboxyl intermediates to the alpha-amino acid.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Hydrolysis of Strecker aminonitriles is the accepted final step to amino acids in Miller-type synthesis. The research emphasizes that isoleucine is produced as racemic/isomeric mixtures and that alloisoleucine is co-produced (Miller, 1957; Ring et al., 1972; Parker et al., 2011; Bada & Schroeder, 1975).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface Strecker synthesis of alpha-aminobutyric acid as a lower-homolog control branch\",\n      \"inputs\": [\n        \"mol_010\",\n        \"mol_003\",\n        \"mol_004\"\n      ],\n      \"outputs\": [\n        \"mol_015\"\n      ],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\n        \"sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)\",\n        \"montmorillonite\"\n      ],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"mineral concentration surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"aqueous Strecker chemistry in discharge-fed pools\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Propanal undergoes Strecker reaction with NH3 and HCN to form alpha-aminobutyric acid.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The research explicitly identifies alpha-aminobutyric acid as a readily formed homolog in Miller experiments and meteorites, illustrating how the isoleucine problem is specifically one of branched-carbon precursor availability rather than general amino acid inaccessibility (Ring et al., 1972; Higgs & Pudritz, 2009).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Biochemical/protometabolic conversion of pyruvate-derived network to alpha-ketobutyrate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\n        \"mol_011\",\n        \"mol_005\"\n      ],\n      \"outputs\": [\n        \"mol_012\"\n      ],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [\n        \"null\"\n      ],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\