25; Pulletikurti et al., 2022).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface Bucherer-Bergs conversion of alpha-keto-beta-methylvalerate to isoleucine hydantoin\",\n      \"inputs\": [\n        \"mol_013\",\n        \"mol_003\",\n        \"mol_004\"\n      ],\n      \"outputs\": [\n        \"mol_014\"\n      ],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\n        \"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\",\n        \"montmorillonite\"\n      ],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"mineral concentration surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"cyanide/ammonia-rich surface pools; hydantoin-forming conditions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Alpha-keto acid reacts with cyanide and ammonia to form a hydantoin intermediate via Bucherer-Bergs chemistry.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Bucherer-Bergs chemistry was demonstrated as a bridge between alpha-keto acids and amino acids in prebiotic settings and is described in the report as general, though not specifically demonstrated for isoleucine's keto acid precursor. Thus the endpoint chemistry is literature-grounded, while precursor availability remains speculative (Pulletikurti et al., 2022).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface hydrolysis of isoleucine hydantoin to isoleucine\",\n      \"inputs\": [\n        \"mol_014\"\n      ],\n      \"outputs\": [\n        \"mol_009\"\n      ],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\n        \"montmorillonite\",\n        \"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\"\n      ],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"mineral-assisted hydrolysis\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"wet-dry cycling supports hydrolysis and accumulation\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Hydrolytic ring opening and conversion of the hydantoin intermediate yields the alpha-amino acid.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Hydantoin hydrolysis is the expected terminal step of Bucherer-Bergs amino acid synthesis. Included here as a literature-consistent completion of the keto-acid branch, while preserving the caveat that access to mol_013 is unresolved prebiotically (Pulletikurti et al., 2022).\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Volcanic H2S spark-discharge Strecker pathway\",\n      \"description\": \"Core literature-supported terrestrial route: discharge chemistry generates HCN and branched aldehydes, then aqueous Strecker chemistry yields isoleucine.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\n        \"rxn_004\",\n        \"rxn_005\",\n        \"rxn_006\",\n        \"rxn_007\"\n      ],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\n        \"mol_004\",\n        \"mol_007\",\n        \"mol_008\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Reduced-gas spark Strecker pathway\",\n      \"description\": \"Ring et al.-style reduced atmosphere discharge path feeding the same Strecker endpoint through the same convergent hubs.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\n        \"rxn_004\",\n        \"rxn_005\",\n        \"rxn_006\",\n        \"rxn_007\"\n      ],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\n        \"mol_004\",\n        \"mol_007\",\n        \"mol_008\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal carbon feed to surface discharge Strecker route\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal FTT chemistry supplies simple aldehydic feedstocks to surface discharge environments where the key branched aldehyde and isoleucine are formed.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\n        \"rxn_002\",\n        \"rxn_004\",\n        \"rxn_005\",\n        \"rxn_006\",\n        \"rxn_007\"\n      ],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\n        \"mol_006\",\n        \"mol_004\",\n        \"mol_007\",\n       